Here’s the Sabatier reaction and stoichiometric formula:

Reaction Formula


CO_2 + 4H_2 \rightarrow CH_4 + 2H_2O


Stoichiometric Relationships
	•	 1 \, \text{mol of } CO_2  reacts with  4 \, \text{mol of } H_2  to produce:
	•	 1 \, \text{mol of } CH_4  (methane)
	•	 2 \, \text{mol of } H_2O  (water)

Mass Calculations

Reactants:


m_{CO_2} = n_{CO_2} \times M_{CO_2} = 1 \, \text{mol} \times 44.01 \, \frac{\text{g}}{\text{mol}} = 44.01 \, \text{g}


m_{H_2} = n_{H_2} \times M_{H_2} = 4 \, \text{mol} \times 2.016 \, \frac{\text{g}}{\text{mol}} = 8.064 \, \text{g}


Products:


m_{CH_4} = n_{CH_4} \times M_{CH_4} = 1 \, \text{mol} \times 16.04 \, \frac{\text{g}}{\text{mol}} = 16.04 \, \text{g}


m_{H_2O} = n_{H_2O} \times M_{H_2O} = 2 \, \text{mol} \times 18.015 \, \frac{\text{g}}{\text{mol}} = 36.03 \, \text{g}


Mass Conservation Check


\text{Total Mass of Reactants: } m_{CO_2} + m_{H_2} = 44.01 \, \text{g} + 8.064 \, \text{g} = 52.074 \, \text{g}


\text{Total Mass of Products: } m_{CH_4} + m_{H_2O} = 16.04 \, \text{g} + 36.03 \, \text{g} = 52.07 \, \text{g}

\[
\therefore \text{Mass is conserved: } 52.074 \, \text{g} \approx 52.07 \, \text{g}
\]

Energy Considerations
	1.	Electrolysis of Water:

2H_2O + \text{electricity} \rightarrow 2H_2 + O_2

Energy input:  \sim 50 \, \text{kWh per kg of } H_2 .
	2.	Sabatier Reaction:

CO_2 + 4H_2 \rightarrow CH_4 + 2H_2O

Energy released:  \Delta H = -165 \, \frac{\text{kJ}}{\text{mol}} \, \text{(exothermic)} .

Let me know if you’d like additional steps or refinements!
